HHIINNTTSS
       ffaallccoo uses the toolswatch/vfeed database. The database is updated every
       week  or  two. Update this database in a cron job. with the --uu followed
       by --cc.

       To regularly search for a group of libraries, apps and  operating  sys-
       tems,  put  the  information in a watchfile and run vfeed --ff watchfile.
       The format of each watch item in the file is packagename:version .

       If you are doing regular software builds, for example using  make,  you
       can  use  ffaallccoo with the the --bb option. If ffaallccoo finds a match, it will
       return an error, the make will exit, and you  will  have  to  determine
       whether  the  bug reported has a security impact on your project and if
       you need to update to that newer package.

       Getting aquinted with packagenames as used in NVD _C_V_E ffaallccoo is only  as
       good  as the package name and version information you give it. Start by
       just using ffaallccoo --nn to see if you are using the correct name.  You  can
       also  search  the  vfeed.db  database  using the toolswatch vfeedcli or
       sqlite to see how you need to name your package name to  be  compatible
       with  the CPE names used in the database. To examine the CPE dictionary
       look at: https://nvd.nist.gov/cpe.cfm

